      "location":"Los Angeles",
      "type":"Full Time",
      "description":"<p>Factual is looking for a scrappy engineer to help our customers\u2019 engineering teams understand, integrate with, deploy, debug, and troubleshoot our software and APIs.  You have been the problem solver of last resort, capable of diagnosing and resolving issues in production environments, and finding and implementing workarounds when necessary. You have described the implementation and behavior of software systems to people inside and outside of your organization, in-person, over the phone, and through IM and email. You\u2019ve explained your systems to people of varying degrees of technical aptitude, ranging from \u201cnot technical at all,\u201d to your coworker engineers who are working on the project every day.</p>\n\n<p>This job is ideal for someone who likes to spend part of the day talking to people, part doing forensic work sifting through log files and telemetry data, part hacking together simple demos and documentation that helps customers understand complex software.</p>\n\n<p>Requirements:</p>\n\n<p>It\u2019s okay if you\u2019re self-taught, but you need to know stuff.\nOutstanding English verbal and written communication\nAbility to debug applications on the JVM\nAbsolute comfort with Linux command line tools\nCompetence in Java\nCompetence in bash AND at least one scripting language (e.g. python, ruby, perl)\nKnowledge of enough networking to troubleshoot connectivity problems\nNice to haves:\nCompetence in Clojure\nEnthusiasm for picking up and quickly integrating new tools: web APIs, open source projects, and software developed internally.\nA skill for debugging remote systems, working from stack traces, heap dumps, and remote telemetry. The ability to make the jump from from \u201cit started doing this wrong thing\u201d to \u201cthe problem is on this line of code\u201d (and, hopefully, \u201chere\u2019s a workaround to use while we develop a long-term fix\u201d).\nA bit of tolerance for repeating yourself, to new customers &amp; new hires, and noticing when the same questions being asked over and overs means that the documentation needs updating.</p>\n\n<p>Nice to haves:</p>\n\n<p>Competence in Clojure\nEnthusiasm for picking up and quickly integrating new tools: web APIs, open source projects, and software developed internally.\nA skill for debugging remote systems, working from stack traces, heap dumps, and remote telemetry. The ability to make the jump from from \u201cit started doing this wrong thing\u201d to \u201cthe problem is on this line of code\u201d (and, hopefully, \u201chere\u2019s a workaround to use while we develop a long-term fix\u201d).\nA bit of tolerance for repeating yourself, to new customers &amp; new hires, and noticing when the same questions being asked over and overs means that the documentation needs updating.</p>\n",
